textDisplay: As someone who grew up with bedrock, I have to say once I got a computer, I definitely prefer java, and I will try and give my unbiased experiences with bedrock, so first of all, fps, bedrock ran way smoother but I felt that the UI was so unbearably slow like setting took a decade to load also the optimisation mods on java makes me run a lot better on bedrock at all times and I know many people say mods aren’t a good argument but if their free (mostly) and east to install I don’t see why they can’t be used in debates , next up the main argument I got at school, bridging, I don’t like it, I play a lot of multiplayer servers and I just don’t like how on bedrock anyone can just bridge to your base in 2 seconds when the matches start, and now a few rapid fire ones, bedrock redstone is not as good as java, I’m not going to say it’s bad immediately but because of the less power capability it’s not as fun to make like qasy connectivity and block updates among many more however it does have some benefits like components are water loggable, movable tile entities and pistons can redirect redstone, ok I swear I’m nearly done blasting bedrock cuz I do have some java arguments too but the nether roof is dumb on bedrock, I know it’s a glitch but it’s a useful one and mojang has intentionally decided to keep it, but not in bedrock and finally the big one, the marketplace, more specifically minecoins i normally try to defend my point but I think I speak for everyone, they’re dumb, java has maps of the same quality for free, ok ok I’m done, now for java, now I’m not trying to be biased but don’t have as much criticism for java but I do have some points, first is the lack of cross platform and that the complete non existence of it, bedrock is so good as in you can play in a PC with a phone, PS, Xbox, Nintendo switch and many more and in java not only do you have to pay to play with friends except for things like aternos (thank you aternos) but you can only play with PC players which has the argument of making things more balanced as PC players aren’t up against phones it still kinda sucks. Also capes are so rare in java, I have the migrator and that one you get for buying both bedrock and java but no one I know has any. Soo In conclusion despite all ups and downs of all versions (I didn’t mention education edition as i felt it to be nothing but a one time gimmick) I think that the best version is LEGACY CONSOLE… no I’m joking I personally say java is better but bedrock does also have a LOT of benefits and I don’t think anyone is wrong for preferring a certain version, like I said I grew up with bedrock but I still prefer java.

textDisplay:
To start coding in 2023 and embark on your programming journey, follow these steps:

Choose a Programming Language:

Research and select a programming language based on your interests and goals. Popular options include Python, JavaScript, Java, C++, or Ruby.
Consider factors such as community support, job market demand, and the language's suitability for your intended projects.
Set Up Your Development Environment:

Install the necessary software and tools for coding. This typically includes a text editor or Integrated Development Environment (IDE) specific to your chosen programming language.
Ensure you have a compiler or interpreter if required for your language.
Learn the Basics:

Start with the fundamentals of programming, such as variables, data types, operators, and control flow.
Understand concepts like loops, conditional statements, and functions.
Get comfortable with basic syntax and coding conventions.
Practice, Practice, Practice:

Begin coding small projects or exercises to reinforce your understanding.
Build simple programs or solve coding challenges to apply what you've learned.
Explore online coding platforms or join coding communities to practice and collaborate with others.
Expand Your Knowledge:

Dive deeper into your chosen programming language, exploring advanced topics and features.
Learn about data structures, algorithms, and design patterns to improve your problem-solving abilities.
Familiarize yourself with libraries, frameworks, and tools commonly used in the language ecosystem.
Work on Real-World Projects:

Apply your skills by working on practical projects. Start with small, manageable projects and gradually tackle more complex ones.
Build personal projects or contribute to open-source projects to gain experience and showcase your work.
Seek Learning Resources:

Utilize online tutorials, documentation, books, and video courses to enhance your knowledge.
Join coding communities, attend meetups, or participate in coding bootcamps for additional learning opportunities.
Collaborate and Seek Feedback:

Engage with other programmers and seek feedback on your code.
Collaborate on projects with others to learn from their experience and improve your teamwork and communication skills.
Stay Updated:

Keep up with the latest trends, updates, and best practices in the programming world.
Follow industry blogs, subscribe to relevant newsletters, and participate in online forums to stay informed.

textDisplay:
Order of Operations memorising trick: "BODMAS"
B – Brackets
O – Order of powers or roots
D – Division
M – Multiplication
A – Addition
S – Subtraction.
The order of the letter in the word BODMAS is the same order you'd use in order of operations Brackets first, powers or roots second, division 3rd, multiplication 4th, addition 5th and subtraction last. Hopefully I'm making sense😅

7:06:30

If a string only contains a number, and we subtract, multiply or divide, Javascript will automatically convert that string into a number and do math to give you a result

Then earlier, why did we have to write let cost = Number(inputElement.value) to do the calculation cost = cost + 10?

The answer is : Because javascript converts a string of only digits to a number when it's subtraction, multiplication or division. Not for addition, because the plus symbol (+) has another meaning of concatenation for strings which takes priority over it's meaning of addition for integers when one of the operands is a string

textDisplay:
TL;DR: half of Java’s bad reputation comes from how programming in it is taught. (That and the lack of something like C++’s option of operator overriding - charAt is a stupid method)
I’m pretty sure that Java would have a much better reputation if it wasn’t taught with the, “everything needs to be a style-compliant Object” bs. Like, yes, the way that you associate data with methods in Java is “objects”, but there’s a huge difference between writing a style-compliant object that’s suitable for API use and a quick internal datastore (I.e. no need for getters and setters when your object is purely for internal use).
Well, that and the weird aversion to some nice procedural code that seems to permeate Java courses.
Like, yes, shorter methods are easier to read, but if you’re doing a bunch of work on a few numbers, you shouldn’t be making a tree of calls.
textOriginal:

Well, that and the weird aversion to some nice procedural code that seems to permeate Java courses.
Like, yes, shorter methods are easier to read, but if you’re doing a bunch of work on a few numbers, you shouldn’t be making a tree of calls.

textDisplay:
It always amazes me how software engineers can complain about the smallest and and most insignificant inconveniences but at the same time write shitty hacky code because "can't be assed to do it properly right now, will fix later".

As somebody that has only been a software engineer for 3 years most of these things are complaining at such a high level that my reaction is "yeah just let them ramble."
Whether you type print() or println() or System.out,println() literally doesn't change anything. It doesn't make the code more readable, it doesn't make it less readable, it doesn't make typing the code any faster because it gets auto completed anyway. Same can be said about many of the things senior devs complain about when they talk about the semantics / syntax of individual languages.

The changes are good and I welcome them, they're nice to have. But that's about it.

And, unpopular opinion:
1:55 that string templates stuff looks less readable to me than just concatenating strings "like you're in kindergarden". Yes, I know there are certain cases in which this will be more readable, I can think of a few right now. But truthfully, most of the time, this is probably going to end up making code less readable. In my opinion, anyway.

But hey, if this means people will stop using the ridiculously verbose StringBuilder and the totally unreadable String.format I'm all for it.

textDisplay: 3:24 I should point out that the meme is a bit harsh, because in this case, it isn't correct to treat strings as arrays of characters, they are not. In Java, the String class is encoded using UCS-2 aka UTF-16. In Java, a character (char) is a 2-byte type that used to represent a Unicode UCS-1 code point. However, that was only sufficient when the number of code points was less than 65536. Now Unicode has 1+ million. So UCS-1 was extended into UTF-16 which allows for some special pairs of 2-byte chars to be combined together into a 4-byte character, called surrogate pairs, to represent characters beyond the base multilingual plane. In these cases, if you just index a string as an array and get out a char, it might only be half the bytes of a unicode character, and you will experience bugs. Just see how many Java "reverse string" methods fail when using emojis. All this being said, Java String.charAt() is also busted for the same reasons stated above. Really, what we need is an object of a class that represents a "character" in a more abstract sense, regardless of underlying encoding or number of bytes in the buffer where it lives.

textDisplay:
Java is a great first language because of its robust syntax. You have to spell out a lot of what it needs to do without interpreting the code at compile time.

When I learned Java I had enough knowledge to go even deeper with C and find out more nuanced topics like memory management.

Java forces order to your code and while more boilerplate it’s more robust and modular as a result. That is only a good thing I think. Never really saw the drawbacks of that.

Or I could learn something a bit less nuanced like JavaScript, which is looser and more interpretive unlike Java.

textDisplay:
for everyone getting "ImportError: No module named PIL" READ THIS!:

ok so I spent about 48 hours (Took me a long time.. I'm a noob lol) trying to figure out why my system was giving me this. What's happening is, your terminal is running an older version of Python. The PIL module and pip we installed were for Python3.

open terminal type in "python --version" it'll probably tell you your default version.

now you can run this command >> "alias python=python3" buuuuut we don't wanna do this every time you open the terminal or your VSCode.

so you need to create a symlink.

to do this you need to find out where your Python3 is actually located.

open a terminal and type in "ls -l /usr/local/bin/python*"

locate any of the lines that say python and the version number. Mines was "3.11" yours could be different at the time you read this.

next you run "ln -s -f /usr/local/bin/python3.11 /usr/local/bin/python". You might say "But this didn't work for me either :(" that's fine...

Run it as admin by adding sudo to the front. "sudo ln -s -f /usr/local/bin/python3.11 /usr/local/bin/python"

It'll require your password and BOOM, complete. Now we can go back to this tutorial LMAO.

You may need to run this in VSCode as well. Then restart and type "python --version". It should give you the current version you have.

LIKE this comment if it helped and maybe he can Pin it for others that struggled like me.

Happy coding.

One pdf is 1 page, the other is 4 pages.  My output PDF is 11 pages, creating duplicate pages in the merge.  Any quick troubleshooting ideas?  I am pretty sure my code is identical.

import PyPDF2
import sys
import os

merger = PyPDF2.PdfMerger()

for file in os.listdir(os.curdir):
    if file.endswith(".pdf"):
        merger.append(file)
    merger.write("combinedBSUniDocs.pdf")

textDisplay: Quick note for those who may get confused (like I did): the YouTube script won't download 4K video - it won't even download 1080p. Due to YouTube's use of the DASH protocol for higher resolutions, the max resolution that this script can handle is 720p. DASH downloads audio and video separately and you need to post-process to combine them, using something like ffmpeg.
textOriginal: Quick note for those who may get confused (like I did): the YouTube script won't download 4K video - it won't even download 1080p. Due to YouTube's use of the DASH protocol for higher resolutions, the max resolution that this script can handle is 720p. DASH downloads audio and video separately and you need to post-process to combine them, using something like ffmpeg.

textDisplay:
1) this seems to imply that Neural Networks are used in Deep Learning only. They are not. It is the number of node layers, or depth, of neural networks that distinguishes a single neural network from a deep learning algorithm, which must have more than three (quoting IBM documentation there). Pretty much all ML or what marketing calls "AI" uses Neural Nets.

2) The claim that Neural Nets simulate the way the brain works is rather strong, given that no one yet knows exactly how the brain does what it does - no one understands how neurons work. Each neuron in your brain has many thousands of connections. There is NO ONE who knows all that neurons are doing with those, nor anyone who understands what is going on inside a human neuron. So how can anyone but a marking department claim a neural network "simulates" what no one understands? This doesn't mean that ML cannot simulate handing of input and output that obtains similar results that a human might, or do some things even better - but that doesn't mean it is simulating a human mind. An old TI Calculator can do some Math a lot faster and more accurately than you can. Does it mean it is thinking like a human brain? We know it''s not.

3) The claim that "we don't always know how the system came up with that" is also kind of a "marketing" thing, in that programmers do know exactly what the code in a neural network is doing. But they do use math like stochastic gradient descent, an algorithm which uses randomness in order to find a set of weights for mapping from inputs to outputs for the training data. Given the very large number of such "neurons" in deep learning code -- while it is fully known how those are generated -- given the randomization, no one can really "know" (or for marketing purposes "understand") how those are all set - (i.e. for example be able to to keep in mind the weights that all those are set to), thus the claim "we don't know what its doing". But its not some magic woo woo.

textDisplay:
I would consider this definition of AI to be insufficient for its common or even academic usage.

Example 1: A computer exceeds human ability at counting, arithmetic, multiplication and many other "basic" computational abilities that are generally not considered AI

Example 2: Computers have yet to (generally) equal or exceed humans in many of the most common "AI" spaces, such as conversation. Although you could argue the goal of these spaces is to do exactly that.

As such I prefer Christopher Reisbeck's definition that AI refers to doing things with computers that humans are generally better at. (he frames it as the question: "Why are computers so dumb" or why are humans better at X)

textDisplay:
Few Notes :

Mean Squared Error is much more used than Mean Absolute Error
Prediction is very general, it would better to regression in the types of neural network
Feed Forward Neural Networks are a bunch of linear layers stacked upon each other with a non-linear layer(often called activation layer)between them.
Convolutional neural networks are a type of normal feed forward feed forward neural network
Convolutional Neural Networks are used a lot for images, but text is normally not passed through Convolutional Networks. Recurrent neural nets are more useful than Convolutional Neural Nets for text.

I think you have confused loss functions (which are the ones minimized by the optimizer of choice) and ways to validate a trained model (accuracy, mean absolute deviation).

Popular loss functions include cross-entropy losses for classification problems and mean squared error for regression problems. These are differentiable everywhere, which is not the case for functions like accuracy or mean absolute deviation.

Nevertheless, thank you very much for the concise introduction to this topic. As your quality standards are very high, I am sure you will find a way to fix this small error.

textDisplay:
Pretty good explanation, but not perfect in my opinion. You mention the acquisition, cleaning and division of data into training sets and test sets, which is true for so called supervised learning, but this isn't the case in all types of machine learning. Some problems have no clear data or an easy way to divide data, such as when using reinforcement learning to train agents to play games. In this example, the model learns by performing actions in a simulated game environment. So the data is generated on the fly, and it's not really possible to divide it into different sets.

Just wanted to clarify this because I think machine learning is commonly misinterpreted as supervised deep learning (not saying you did, but others might) when in reality it is much more. But I like that you're delving into these types of topics, and would love to see more of it!

textDisplay: No half-competent C++ programmer would routinely use malloc/free, or even new/delete when it can be easily avoided. Fun fact: C++ actually has automatic memory and resource management. Well, kind of, at least. It's called RAII. The problem is that it's not enforced, and sometimes tricky to get right. This is where Rust and its borrow checker comes in - it picks up C++' idea of automatic resource management, makes it mandatory and goes out of its way to keep you from getting it wrong.

textDisplay:
> mutable values...are stored in the heap

This is incorrect, and it's a pretty fundamental point. Rust is happy to have mutable values on the stack. The stack vs heap distinction in Rust is similar to the same in C++: objects need to live on the heap if their size is unknown at compile time (as the video mentions) or if their lifetime isn't limited to any particular scope. In Rust this is often done with Vec, Box, or Arc, much like C++ would use vector, unique_ptr, or shared_ptr.

Rust's unique approach to mutability is unrelated to the stack/heap distinction. The rule in Rust is that a mutable object can't be aliased; there can only be a single, unique reference to it while it's being mutated. This dovetails very closely with the ownership and borrowing rules that keep track of object lifetimes and prevent use-after-free bugs. These are the parts of Rust that make it really unique.

textDisplay:
Man, I still have my plans for my GSD language... The cold compile times would be atrocious, but great incremental, and such great unorthodox features, people would either love it, or just be too confused by it being too alien...
GSD stands for: Getting Shit Done
- The main thing I want is a heavy consistent suport for compile time evaluation, which all languages need (macros, templates,...), but it's rarely elevated to a first class citizen. Instead it should be the basis.
- And to minimize annoyances like boilerplate, or convoluted build tools, mainly static linking, rich type inference even in fn headers (really, all functions would be more templates, instantiated depending on how they are used) (unless ABI, and restricted for library API), and so much more... - I want, what the name says.

A little like Zig, but a lot more capable, and for example: Types are "just" compile time objects that implement an interface TypeGuard, etc.

//why did I comment this? ... idk... I'm depressed, and felt inspired... It's just a language I dream about, and while I have an idea on how to write it, I ~know I will never have the energy, nor time for it, and I know it will never get popular even if I did make a prototype ...
I have thousands and thousands of lines of notes, thinking about the design... Why can I not just be content with the annoying stuff we have...
I wish I would at least write an article about the ideas I have - Maybe people would like it. Maybe some language could pick up the main ideals... But I don't even have the "energy" for that...

textDisplay:
0:37, C has this restriction. With C++ you can also do this, as well as higher-level methods too.
0:51, C++ can use both mutable or not on the stack. The condition is if their memory size don't pass a certain amount of memory. 1:05, whenever it does, 1 can use smart-pointer, that does just what you showed here - and prevents the dangling issue.
1:19, you can pass a reference for that, as well as any other variable/object/pointer. Pointer is specially useful in situations where things can go wrong, allowing to represent the case by a null value, which is a nice idea.
Race conditions: since 2011 (C++11) we have the <atomic> library, which forbids data racing at compile-time.
1:47, finally something C++ hasn't: assigning numbers by a growing order, right at the declaration. But you can always define your custom constructor for that.

1:19, you can pass a reference for that, as well as any other variable/object/pointer. Pointer is specially useful in situations where things can go wrong, allowing to represent the case by a null value, which is a nice idea.
Race conditions: since 2011 (C++11) we have the <atomic> library, which forbids data racing at compile-time.

textDisplay: Respectfully, there are a lot of misconceptions in this video. C++ also has drop semantics and you can write memory safe code with it when you don't use raw pointers at all. The reason Rust is memory safe is because it doesn't allow you to use raw pointers by default and checks reference validity at compile time, which C++ could only really do at run-time last time I checked.
textOriginal: Respectfully, there are a lot of misconceptions in this video. C++ also has drop semantics and you can write memory safe code with it when you don't use raw pointers at all. The reason Rust is memory safe is because it doesn't allow you to use raw pointers by default and checks reference validity at compile time, which C++ could only really do at run-time last time I checked.
